AGI -&nbsp;The European Union welcomes some of the companies with the greatest gender equality in the world. It has achieved historical progress over the last five years with the norms on wage transparency, &nbsp; the balance between work and private life, &nbsp; gender balance in the Cdas of companies&nbsp; and the&nbsp; violence against women. But that's not enough. Just browse the last gender equality report to realize it: a woman out of three has suffered violence; One out of six was victim of sexual violence. Women have fewer jobs and when they have a job they are paid less than their fellow men.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
The European Commission has published a Roadmap to make society fairer. But there is also the commitment of the European Parliament, of many Italian MEPs. For example, they do not forgive the EU states that they have not approved last year the definition of rape as a European crime.
&nbsp;
" Sex without consent is rape. Only one yes is a yes," he insists on speaking to AGI the Euro MP of Forza Italia (Ppe), Caterina Chinnici. "Continuing and completing the work begun in the previous legislature on the directive on the fight against violence against women and domestic violence, so that the crime of rape is a European crime, is my priority," she points out.
&nbsp;
He joins the battle, from the benches of the Greens, Benedetta Scuderi, one of the youngest faces of the emicycle. "That was a missed opportunity but you have to do so to recover. Also because consent would become a focal point," he explains. "The burden of proof must not fall on victims, as unfortunately often happens now in several European states," he adds.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
"Let's talk about a serious offence that leaves unfortunately also long-term consequences on the victims", agrees the League MEP, Isabella Tovaglieri, who nevertheless expresses "any doubt on the method, since there are discordant opinions and many doubts about the fact that it is a competence of the EU, but rather of the Member States".
&nbsp;
Political commitment to the European Parliament in favour of equality is not limited to the battle against violence. There are many other battles (small and large) that however make the difference in the daily life of millions of women. The PD MEP, Vice-President of the S&amp;d Group, Camilla Laureti, is engaged for example on the wage gap.
&nbsp;
"We must invest in women's empowerment because overcoming gender gap is a big question of justice, but also a big question of development and growth for Europe," he said. And it must be done in all sectors. "I take care of agriculture and it is my priority to continue the commitment to foster the protagonism of farmers, overcoming the difficulties that they encounter for example in access to credit and land, linked also to the permanence of prejudices and cultural stereotypes," he points out.
&nbsp;
"Women-led farms, which are around 30% in Europe, are a model on innovation and therefore sustainability, as well as the multifunctionality of the sector. Not supporting them would be a strategic mistake for the future of agriculture," he adds.
&nbsp;
Once again the gap emerges, the absence of women. And - as the Euro MP of the 5-star Movement denounces, Carolina Morace - it is often an absence that is also noted in the European institutions. "Too often, in the institutional events organized in the European Parliament, for example, the majority of experts invited as speakers are men," he says. "It is uncompromising that it is not born from the lack of experts, but for consolidated dynamics in the selection of speakers, which do not fully take into account the presence of qualified professionals in different sectors". Morace, former female national coach and first woman to enter the Hall of hunger of Italian football, proposes to "create a database of experts divided into thematic areas to which all MEPs can access when organizing events".
&nbsp;
It would be a practical and immediate support for all MPs, helping to make events more balanced and representative of society. In Scuderi there is no equality in the rooms where decisions are taken, even in the European Parliament. "In this mandate there are fewer young people and women, not to mention the presence of women in the European Commission. We have very few and very few young people in politics also in Italy, where, moreover, the passive electorate to 25 years for the European elections further limits their entry, unlike the other States that do not apply this threshold. In fact, the European population is legally discriminating, and this is made possible by the attitude of a Europe which does not want to become a union of political rights and union, but only of market". &nbsp;

